b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48361.htm)  [Next](sbe48363.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n18\\. For this very reason comparisons, such as reflected images of the sun and\nthe like.\n\nBecause Brahman, although abiding in manifold places, ever possesses the\ntwofold characteristics, and hence does not share the imperfections due to\nthose places, scriptural texts illustrate its purity in the midst of inferior\nsurroundings by comparing it to the sun reflected in water, mirrors, and the\nlike. Compare e.g., 'As the one ether is rendered manifold by jars and the\nlike, or as the one sun becomes manifold in several sheets of water; thus the\none Self is rendered manifold by abiding in many places. For the Self of all\nbeings, although one, abides in each separate being and is thus seen as one\nand many at the same time, as the moon reflected in water.'\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 19. But because it is not apprehended like water, there is no\nequality](sbe48363.htm)\n\n"